{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b324b801-fe38-4b1b-bc4a-f496bc898be7","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the simplest option for .NET 8 CPU profiling.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** (Diagnostics Hub) or convert to `.speedscope` for https://speedscope.app:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n### Alternative: PerfView (deeper analysis)\n\nIf you need OS-level context (kernel stacks, GC, I/O):\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\nPerfView.exe collect -Duration:30 -CircularMB:500\n```\n\nPerfView gives richer ETW data but has a steeper learning curve.\n\n**TL;DR:** Start with `dotnet-trace` + `cpu-sampling`. Escalate to PerfView if you need kernel-level detail.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c2f53d3f-9934-4532-86bd-52a3da8071f6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task. I should provide a concise, practical answer.\n\nThe best tool for this is `dotnet-trace` or PerfView. For CPU profiling specifically, `dotnet-trace` with the cpu-sampling profile is the simplest, but PerfView gives richer ETW-based analysis. Since they have admin access and it's Windows, PerfView is the gold standard for CPU investigations on Windows.\n\nLet me give a concise recommendation.","outputTokens":455},"id":"8855e536-47c5-454d-8743-70aca04a33e2","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:50:07.980Z","parentId":"7a9b1615-dd83-4a10-aef1-81b6946e8657"}
